ls0 ws0">human knowledge. They are things that happen outside the </div><div class="t m16e x1d he ye5 ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">known bounds of science and natural law; they can&apos;t be explained by </div><div class="t m278 x1d he y74a ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">common physical phenomena. That&apos;s why, in fact, they&apos;re called miracles. </div><div class="t mac x1e he y523 ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The Bible records about thirty-five miracles that Jesus performed </div><div class="t m2ab x1d he y50e ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">while in the flesh. Each one served a specific purpose, and all of them </div><div class="t m3d5 x1d he y524 ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">together advanced His mission of defeating Satan, death, and sin. </div><div class="t m31a x1d he y74b ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">These miracles also show how closely the conflict between good and </div><div class="t m1c2 x1d he y74c ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">evil is fought in the lives of individuals. </div><div class="t m616 x1e he y527 ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">This week we will study five miracles that focus on how Jesus </div><div class="t m2b7 x1d he y510 ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">brought healing, life, and truth to those who so desperately needed </div><div class="t m617 x1d he y511 ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">them. In addition to illustrating Jesus&apos; power and authority, the </div><div class="t m618 x1d he y34c ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">miracles also testify to His mission as the One sent by the Father to </div><div class="t m11d x1d he y34d ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">save humankind from the consequences of sin, something far beyond </div><div class="t m42a x1d he y34e ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">our capacity—even in the age of the Internet, space shuttles, and limb </div><div class="t m1d4 x1d he y34f ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">transplants—to do for ourselves. Good news, indeed! </div><div class="t m14b x1d he y38b ff2 fsa fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">*(Study this week&apos;s lesson to prepare for Sabbath, March 2.) </div><di